  "solution": {
    "approach": "We need to keep tasks in the order they first appear while ignoring duplicates. A boolean array of size 1001 (since task ≤ 1000) records whether a task has already been seen in the current test case. While reading the N tasks, if a task has not been seen we mark it and append it to the output. This gives O(N) time per test case and O(1) extra space (the fixed-size seen array).",
    "timeComplexity": "O(N) per test case, O(total N) for the whole input.",
    "spaceComplexity": "O(1) auxiliary space (boolean array of size 1001) plus output storage.",
    "code": {
      "C": "",
      "C++": "",
      "Java": "import java.io.*;\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {\n        BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));\n        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();\n        int T = Integer.parseInt(br.readLine().trim());\n        for (int tc = 0; tc < T; tc++) {\n            int N = Integer.parseInt(br.readLine().trim());\n            boolean[] seen = new boolean[1001];\n            for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {\n                int task = Integer.parseInt(br.readLine().trim());\n                if (!seen[task]) {\n                    seen[task] = true;\n                    sb.append(task).append('\\n');\n                }\n            }\n        }\n        System.out.print(sb.toString());\n    }\n}",
      "Python3": "",
      "JavaScript": ""
    }
  },
